The paper deals with the problem of generating high-resolution 3D objects from low-resolution inputs, which is a common problem in computer vision and graphics. The method proposed in the paper involves using deep learning networks to perform super-resolution on the six orthographic depth projections of the object, which can be seen as a form of image processing. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with 3D object representation and reconstruction, which are topics that are often studied in the Graphics (cs.GR) sub-category. The use of deep learning networks also suggests that the paper could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) or Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper's focus on generating high-resolution 3D objects suggests that it could also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category, which deals with the use of neural networks and other computational models inspired by biological systems.
